node.text: During our recent shoot In Iceland of the Fagradalshraun Volcano, I had a few moments to use my drone to capture the volcano from a different perspective, and in the process revealing the epic scale of the lava river that’s grown exponentially during the last few weeks . As soon as I flew close to the volcano, it began erupting... and as I began to fly away avoiding the heat and lava from the volcano, the massive lava field comes into perspective.  Click the IGTV icon to see the full video!

node.text: I am so fortunate to be a member of the TED Speaker community and was so honored when the team at TED asked me to participate in the 2020 TED Countdown global launch.  I was asked create a short visual and a poetic reflection using my photographs to illustrate climate change.  My hope is that this work will open people’s minds and allow them to reflect on how profound the issue of climate change really is.  Congratulations  to the Countdown team at TED for an incredibly successful launch.  I hope to continue to work with TED and all of the other activists in accelerating solutions to the climate crisis.

node.text: Number 17 in my tapestry series.  I was sitting on the edge of a pond in a field when I made this tapestry.  I love the textural & painterly quality that happens when all of these elements are layered into one frame.  Water and grass visually become a woven wool.  Over the last 8 years I’ve been quietly working on a series called “Tapestries” inspired by the great tapestries during the Renaissance. These photographs are made all in camera, multiple exposures & usually happen within 4-8 seconds. They are layered captures of unique moments in time. #water #grass #tapestry #fuji #photography

node.text: I made this photograph of aerospace designer & engineer Burt Rutan & his iconic “White Knight” Space Ship One aircraft for Time Magazine’s “Inventions of the Year 2004” issue.  Burt & I connected, as we both share a child like passion for creating within our respective careers .  I asked him what inspired him to build a ship like this.  He told me he always goes to sleep with a pen & paper beside his bed.  One night he had a dream that he was playing badminton & in the middle of the dream he realized that a shuttlecock floating, suddenly inspired him to create something similar that was aerodynamically unique.  He woke up and started to design what eventually became SpaceShipOne & it’s mothership “White Knight”. In 2004 Rutan & his company Scaled Composites sold this design to Sir Richard Branson who would embark on a 17 year journey to develop the first commercial flight into space.  On July 11th 2021 Branson took flight to the edge of space aboard SpaceShipTwo the direct descendant of Rutan’s creation.  Congratulations to Burt Rutan & Sir Richard for this historic achievement.  Swipe right to see Rutan with his crew from 2004, pilots Mike Melville & Brian Binnie. #time #rutan #space #photography

node.text: Yesterday President Joe Biden signed legislation into law establishing June 19th as “Juneteenth National Independence Day” commemorating the end of slavery in the United States.  This transformative moment in our country’s history reminded me of the day I photographed  Allie C. Peak.  Peak was a member of the Tuskegee Airmen, the first African American Aviators in the armed forces who served in World War II.  Their very existence symbolized the progress our country had made since slavery ended , and yet they were still subject the Jim Crow laws & a segregated military.  When ever I see this photograph I’m reminded of not only of how far we’ve come, but also of the work we have ahead of us. “By making Juneteenth a federal holiday, all Americans can feel the power of this day, and learn from our history— and celebrate progress and grapple with the distance we’ve come & the distance we have to travel”- President Joe Biden  #juneteenth #tuskegeeairmen #civilrights #nationalholiday

node.text: From yesterday’s solar eclipse.  When the sun rose at 5:13am EST it was in mid eclipse.  The entire eclipse lasted 3 1/2 minutes & the peak eclipse time was 5:33am EST.  Solar eclipses occur when the moon crosses between the sun & the Earth which blocks a portion of the suns rays.  In some parts of the Northern Hemisphere the moon looked smaller than the sun, leaving room for bright light to glow around the edges creating a “ring of fire”. #eclipse #solar #ringoffire #sun #moon

node.text:
Earlier this week we celebrated World Oceans Day.  As I reflected on the impact humans have on our planet’s biggest life source, my thoughts kept going back to my 2019 Day to Night shoot in Greenland.
 
I traveled to Ilulissat Greenland in July of 2019 where I witnessed what has become known as The “Great July Melt”, the largest melt of the Greenland Ice sheet in recorded history, in what would amount to 200 billion tons of ice being liquified into the Atlantic Ocean.  When glacial ice melts, caving icebergs release sediments and particles into the seawater, initiating our ocean’s food-chain.  Plankton feed on the sediment, krill eat plankton & the humpback whales feed on the krill.  We assume that the greatest threat of glacial melt will be sea level rise, which will certainly impact major cities & coastlines around the world.  But in creating this image, I discovered that perhaps the greatest threat from glacial melt might be our to ocean’s ability to feed itself.  Without ice the ocean food chain may break.  Creating this photograph opened my eyes to the effects we are having on the Earth’s water.  Let’s look after our oceans, so they will be the planet’s life source for generations to come. #worldoceansday #oceans #glacier #photography #greenland #daytonight
